WEBVTT

00:02.820 --> 00:04.030
<i>- Previously on</i>
<i>"School Spirits..."</i>

00:04.230 --> 00:05.030
- The Split River Police
are considering this

00:05.230 --> 00:06.770
a missing person investigation.

00:06.970 --> 00:08.510
- It's only a matter of time
till they realize you're dead.

00:08.710 --> 00:09.730
all: Hi, Maddie.

00:09.930 --> 00:10.910
- Welcome to
the Split River High

00:11.110 --> 00:12.340
- Afterlife Support Group.
- How'd you die?

00:12.540 --> 00:14.300
- I don't know exactly.
- Oh, you were murdered.

00:14.500 --> 00:15.260
- [bell rings]
- You degenerates are late.

00:15.460 --> 00:17.000
- What do I know?
- You know something.

00:17.200 --> 00:19.010
- No, no, no. Tell me
what the fuck you think I know.

00:20.970 --> 00:22.440
- Why do you have
Maddie's phone?

00:22.640 --> 00:23.270
<i>- I've been hooking up</i>
<i>with this cheerleader.</i>

00:23.470 --> 00:25.010
Maddie didn't know.

00:25.210 --> 00:27.180
<i>I stole Maddie's phone</i>
<i>so I could delete that text.</i>

00:27.380 --> 00:30.980
- I don't know how I'm going to
survive this place without her.

00:40.910 --> 00:43.770
<i>[wistful music]</i>

00:43.960 --> 00:48.030
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:48.230 --> 00:49.730
Thank you, Simon.

00:49.930 --> 00:56.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:02.620 --> 01:04.390
Maddie.

01:04.590 --> 01:06.830
Simon?

01:07.030 --> 01:09.400
What the fuck?

01:09.600 --> 01:12.280
Simon, can you see me?

01:14.110 --> 01:16.200
You can hear me, right?

01:19.640 --> 01:21.410
What's going on?
What's he doing?

01:21.610 --> 01:23.070
Um, forgetting to breathe.

01:23.260 --> 01:24.460
Who are you talking to?

01:24.660 --> 01:26.070
- This has never
happened before.

01:26.270 --> 01:29.260
- I--
- Someone you can't see.

01:31.700 --> 01:33.680
- I'm not sure what
I'm seeing right now.

01:33.880 --> 01:34.860
It's me.

01:35.060 --> 01:36.210
You're seeing me.

01:36.410 --> 01:38.990
And I'm really happy you can.

01:39.190 --> 01:40.130
- Wait. Me too.
I have a million questions.

01:40.330 --> 01:42.260
Me too.

01:42.460 --> 01:45.170
I have a million questions.

01:45.370 --> 01:47.520
I don't think I have answers.

01:47.720 --> 01:49.310
Not yet.

01:49.510 --> 01:52.660
What happened?

01:52.860 --> 01:55.140
I don't know.

01:55.340 --> 01:57.230
Were you hurt?

01:57.430 --> 02:00.100
Are you in pain?

02:00.300 --> 02:01.230
Maybe.

02:01.430 --> 02:03.060
I'm not sure. I can't remember.

02:03.260 --> 02:04.280
But he had your phone.

02:04.480 --> 02:05.720
Xavier had your phone.
I saw it.

02:05.920 --> 02:07.240
- I know. He told his dad
he was intercepting

02:07.440 --> 02:08.630
a text he sent to
Claire Zahler.

02:08.830 --> 02:10.070
Why was he texting Claire?

02:10.270 --> 02:11.850
- 'Cause they were
secretly hooking up.

02:12.050 --> 02:13.550
Hooking up when?

02:13.750 --> 02:15.220
Simon?

02:17.220 --> 02:19.120
Hey. The vigil's over.

02:19.320 --> 02:21.380
People are, like, splitting up
to search the woods.

02:21.580 --> 02:22.910
I traded in our candles
for flashlights

02:23.110 --> 02:24.780
because my phone is on 2%.

02:24.980 --> 02:25.950
And I hate nature.

02:26.150 --> 02:29.350
Mosquitoes think
I'm, like, a food truck.

02:29.550 --> 02:31.960
Who were you talking to?

02:32.160 --> 02:35.570
Myself.

02:35.770 --> 02:37.490
OK.

02:37.690 --> 02:40.360
Are you sure
you're up for this?

02:40.560 --> 02:42.490
Go with her.

02:42.690 --> 02:43.410
There could be answers
out there.

02:43.610 --> 02:45.510
I--I need to know
what happened to me.

02:47.990 --> 02:50.330
OK. OK.

02:50.530 --> 02:52.150
OK, OK, OK!

02:52.350 --> 02:54.460
- Let's go. You ready?
- Yeah.

02:54.660 --> 02:57.420
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

02:57.620 --> 03:04.440
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:06.790 --> 03:09.130
Come on.

03:09.330 --> 03:10.610
Why did he stop seeing me?

03:10.810 --> 03:11.740
- Why do you think
I have all the answers, huh?

03:11.940 --> 03:13.130
I'm still trying to figure out

03:13.330 --> 03:14.740
why "Dances with Wolves" won
seven Oscars.

03:14.940 --> 03:16.310
Charley!

03:16.510 --> 03:17.530
- OK, this unofficial
tour guide gig

03:17.730 --> 03:19.230
doesn't come with, like,
a--a handbook!

03:19.420 --> 03:20.750
He could see me and hear me.

03:20.950 --> 03:22.920
- I--I know, and it was--
it was--it was amazing.

03:23.120 --> 03:24.880
[stammers]

03:25.080 --> 03:26.930
It could have been, like,
a one-time thing, a hiccup or--

03:27.130 --> 03:29.420
- Where are you going?
- To join my search party.

03:32.340 --> 03:34.890
Simon!

03:35.090 --> 03:37.720
Simon!

03:37.920 --> 03:39.520
Wait up.

03:44.040 --> 03:45.210
[sucking sound]

03:45.410 --> 03:46.870
[groans]

03:48.220 --> 03:49.570
[grunts]

03:50.140 --> 03:52.950
<i>[dark synth music]</i>

03:53.150 --> 03:55.960
<i>[vocalizing]</i>

03:56.160 --> 03:57.920
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:58.110 --> 04:01.010
<i>♪ Don't forget me</i>
<i>when I'm gone ♪</i>

04:01.200 --> 04:06.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:07.170 --> 04:11.150
<i>♪ Don't forget me</i>
<i>when I'm long gone ♪</i>

04:11.350 --> 04:18.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:28.740 --> 04:30.820
<i>♪ Don't you forget ♪</i>

04:31.020 --> 04:33.340
<i>♪ Don't forget me</i>
<i>when I'm gone ♪</i>

04:33.540 --> 04:37.390
<i>♪ Don't you forget me</i>
<i>when I'm gone ♪</i>

04:37.590 --> 04:39.700
<i>♪ Don't you forget ♪</i>

04:39.900 --> 04:44.500
<i>♪ Don't forget me</i>
<i>when I'm gone ♪</i>

04:51.460 --> 04:54.060
<i>[quirky music]</i>

04:54.260 --> 04:55.630
- Yeah, I could have
saved you that trip.

04:55.820 --> 04:57.670
Can't jump the fence, remember?

04:57.870 --> 04:59.190
You try to leave campus,

04:59.390 --> 05:01.240
you just bounce right back to
where you croaked.

05:01.440 --> 05:03.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:03.830 --> 05:05.160
- Can Mr. Martin at least
explain to me

05:05.360 --> 05:07.640
why Simon can see me
and no one else can?

05:07.840 --> 05:10.160
- I wouldn't bring that up
just yet.

05:10.360 --> 05:11.770
Why?

05:11.970 --> 05:13.690
- I just worry that
there are others in the group

05:13.890 --> 05:16.650
who might get confused,
needy, greedy.

05:16.850 --> 05:19.210
They might turn you into
a messenger service.

05:19.410 --> 05:20.780
- But--
- Stop, Maddie.

05:20.980 --> 05:23.610
Just keep it to yourself, OK?

05:23.810 --> 05:25.480
Until we figure this all out,
let's--

05:25.680 --> 05:28.450
just you and me, OK?

05:33.420 --> 05:35.590
What are you looking at?

05:37.720 --> 05:39.640
- What are you reading?
- Nothing.

05:42.340 --> 05:47.240
- I suggest you probably
unplug that for a little while.

05:47.440 --> 05:48.900
You should stay home from
school tomorrow, too.

05:49.100 --> 05:50.770
Why?

05:50.970 --> 05:52.200
I don't want to stay home.

05:52.400 --> 05:53.770
- You can't go back
until we find out more.

05:53.970 --> 05:55.990
Dad, if I stay home,

05:56.190 --> 05:58.210
I'm playing into this whole
Hannibal Lecter crap, OK?

05:58.410 --> 06:00.910
They saw you take me away
in the police car.

06:01.110 --> 06:02.610
They think
I'm some kind of sociopath

06:02.800 --> 06:03.610
that needs to be caged.

06:03.810 --> 06:05.520
You need to be here

06:05.720 --> 06:08.830
until we find out what happened
to your friend.

06:09.030 --> 06:10.220
She was more than a friend.

06:10.420 --> 06:14.310
- Well, whatever she is,
whenever she was,

06:14.510 --> 06:15.970
that was her blood on the wall.

06:16.170 --> 06:18.320
- You don't know that,
not for sure.

06:18.520 --> 06:20.280
Yeah, we do.

06:20.470 --> 06:22.450
The lab results came back.

06:22.650 --> 06:24.420
That's definitely her blood.

06:34.870 --> 06:36.810
You need to stay away
from the school

06:37.010 --> 06:39.700
until I tell you
it's time to go back.

06:59.240 --> 07:01.230
[muffled scream]

07:01.430 --> 07:06.060
- There's an old cider mill
off Route 47,

07:06.260 --> 07:09.410
and my parents would toss us
in the Dodge Coronet.

07:09.610 --> 07:13.420
We'd each get a bag of
warm, greasy donuts.

07:13.610 --> 07:15.690
That was my idea of nirvana.

07:19.350 --> 07:21.380
What's that about?

07:21.580 --> 07:22.770
Is there a problem?

07:22.970 --> 07:24.770
- He always leaves me
with the worst one.

07:24.970 --> 07:25.820
- What do you mean?
It's lemon glazed.

07:26.020 --> 07:28.470
Nobody wants a lemon donut.

07:28.670 --> 07:30.000
Guys, the subject is nirvana.

07:30.200 --> 07:31.650
- No, the subject
is entitlement.

07:31.850 --> 07:33.300
Oh, OK, I'm entitled

07:33.500 --> 07:35.180
because I like
anything filled with jelly.

07:35.380 --> 07:36.530
- Yeah, that makes sense.
- You take the last jelly,

07:36.720 --> 07:38.880
I will rip off your arm and
beat you with the wet end.

07:39.070 --> 07:39.880
- Rhonda, I'm the one that
boosted these from

07:40.080 --> 07:40.960
the faculty lounge
in the first place.

07:41.160 --> 07:41.970
- Guys--
- Just be grateful.

07:42.160 --> 07:43.840
Guys, we're talking nirvana.

07:44.040 --> 07:45.060
- Technically,
there is no wet end.

07:45.250 --> 07:46.710
- We don't bleed out.
- You know what?

07:46.910 --> 07:48.020
Can I be excused, please?

07:48.210 --> 07:49.500
I would like to eat
my donut in peace.

07:49.690 --> 07:50.840
- And he gets excused for that.
More entitlement.

07:51.040 --> 07:52.150
- No, it's not entitlement,
Rhonda, OK?

07:52.350 --> 07:53.930
It's about--
it's about digestion.

07:54.130 --> 07:56.980
- Has anybody ever been
seen by a living person?

07:57.180 --> 07:59.590
[clears throat]

07:59.790 --> 08:03.420
That doesn't happen, hon.

08:03.620 --> 08:05.030
- Has anyone here ever
talked to a living person?

08:05.230 --> 08:07.120
- Oh, you know what?
Is--uh--

08:07.320 --> 08:09.650
is this a blueberry
or a raisin?

08:09.840 --> 08:11.870
- Dude, how many things could
you possibly be allergic to?

08:12.060 --> 08:13.170
You know you can't
die twice, right?

08:13.370 --> 08:15.130
- Too soon.
- OK. I think--

08:15.330 --> 08:18.220
I think perhaps you're asking
the wrong question, Maddie.

08:18.420 --> 08:19.830
Let's rephrase it.

08:20.030 --> 08:21.610
How do we say goodbye
to the living?

08:21.810 --> 08:22.830
That wasn't my question.

08:23.030 --> 08:25.620
- How do we close
the proverbial book?

08:25.820 --> 08:27.400
Well, I'll tell you how.

08:27.600 --> 08:30.410
Before we wrap up today,
I'm giving you an assignment.

08:30.600 --> 08:31.670
You mean like homework?

08:31.870 --> 08:33.670
- It sounds like
you're struggling.

08:33.870 --> 08:35.060
Write your obituary.

08:35.260 --> 08:36.500
Uh, no.

08:36.700 --> 08:37.980
- Everybody here
has written one.

08:38.180 --> 08:40.550
- It helps us focus on
the highlights of our lives,

08:40.750 --> 08:41.940
the sweet victories.

08:42.140 --> 08:42.810
- I've gotten out of
writing papers before

08:43.010 --> 08:44.290
because of cramps.

08:44.490 --> 08:46.510
I'm pretty sure death counts
as a good excuse.

08:46.710 --> 08:48.120
This isn't busywork, Maddie.

08:48.320 --> 08:50.160
[slurps]

08:50.360 --> 08:52.570
Oh, my god.

08:54.960 --> 08:56.390
- So no one here
has ever talked with

08:56.590 --> 08:59.580
someone who's not dead?

09:04.760 --> 09:07.010
- You here late today
or early for tomorrow?

09:07.210 --> 09:09.180
- We just got back from
searching the woods.

09:09.380 --> 09:11.190
Oh, right.

09:11.380 --> 09:13.320
Find anything?

09:13.520 --> 09:16.100
Of course not.

09:16.300 --> 09:18.190
Why do they want to look
in the dark scary places

09:18.390 --> 09:21.160
when most of the important
shit's stuck under a desk?

09:24.780 --> 09:27.160
Did you find something?

09:27.360 --> 09:29.030
Me?

09:29.230 --> 09:30.420
Hell, no.

09:30.620 --> 09:32.080
I'm just saying
I can't speak to no woods,

09:32.270 --> 09:33.030
but there's plenty of crap
around here

09:33.230 --> 09:35.380
to give you chicken bumps,

09:35.580 --> 09:38.050
There's scars everywhere.

09:47.760 --> 09:50.220
[sighs]

09:50.420 --> 09:56.680
[phone vibrating]

10:10.610 --> 10:13.250
[clears throat]

10:13.450 --> 10:16.120
May I interrupt?

10:16.320 --> 10:19.040
- What's that?
- Some sample obituaries.

10:19.230 --> 10:22.040
Just to inspire,
get your juices flowing.

10:22.240 --> 10:23.650
I'm not writing that.

10:23.850 --> 10:25.050
Sorry.

10:26.750 --> 10:29.130
- Maddie,
I know it's a lot to ask,

10:29.330 --> 10:31.790
but you're gonna have to
trust me.

10:31.990 --> 10:32.960
- Yeah, I'm sitting here
in hell right now

10:33.160 --> 10:36.360
because I trusted
the wrong person.

10:36.560 --> 10:39.800
- Well, hell doesn't have
views like this.

10:39.990 --> 10:42.770
Wanna bet?

10:44.460 --> 10:46.320
This assignment

10:46.520 --> 10:48.800
might bring you some closure
from that world.

10:49.000 --> 10:50.940
You don't get it, do you?

10:51.140 --> 10:53.460
I'm not looking for closure.

10:53.660 --> 10:55.160
You know, I have to talk to
my best friend again,

10:55.360 --> 10:57.200
and I have to figure out
what happened to me.

10:57.400 --> 10:59.080
- But that won't change
the fact that you're here.

10:59.270 --> 11:02.780
- You know,
maybe I'm not ready to be here.

11:02.970 --> 11:06.820
You know, I wasn't done with
my life, Mr. Martin.

11:07.020 --> 11:08.910
I have things I want to do.

11:09.110 --> 11:11.400
And I have people who need me.

11:16.190 --> 11:19.400
- Do those people live near
the water tower?

11:19.600 --> 11:21.750
Yeah.

11:21.950 --> 11:24.800
As a matter of fact, she does.

11:25.000 --> 11:28.670
And believe me,
losing my dad was hard enough.

11:28.870 --> 11:30.930
This is gonna break my mother.

11:31.130 --> 11:34.330
People can surprise you.

11:34.530 --> 11:37.290
Not really.

11:37.490 --> 11:39.070
It's kind of hard to top
her showing up to

11:39.270 --> 11:45.950
my fifth grade concert tanked
and walking through a harp.

11:46.150 --> 11:47.690
Not much surprises you
after that.

11:47.890 --> 11:52.910
- Maddie,
this is still very fresh.

11:53.110 --> 11:54.130
It gets easier.

11:54.330 --> 11:57.090
Does it?

11:57.290 --> 11:59.750
Who's gonna take away
her car keys, huh?

11:59.940 --> 12:02.570
Who's gonna make sure
she turns the stove off?

12:02.770 --> 12:05.320
Who's gonna make sure she falls
asleep in her bed at night?

12:05.510 --> 12:08.280
<i>[somber music]</i>

12:08.470 --> 12:11.800
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:12.000 --> 12:14.020
Look, all I'm saying

12:14.220 --> 12:16.460
is if you cling to
what you left behind,

12:16.660 --> 12:18.720
you'll prolong your pain.

12:18.920 --> 12:22.460
And give a lot of people here
false hopes.

12:22.660 --> 12:24.680
It's cruel to let anyone
believe that they can go back

12:24.880 --> 12:29.860
when they have worked so hard
to move forward.

12:30.060 --> 12:32.780
You don't want teasing the dead
on your resume.

12:32.980 --> 12:39.800
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:12.610 --> 13:13.690
[door opens]

13:13.890 --> 13:14.990
- Please tell me
the coffee is ready.

13:15.190 --> 13:16.340
It is.

13:16.540 --> 13:17.560
Wake up, cherry pop.

13:17.760 --> 13:19.580
It's the best time of the day.

13:22.010 --> 13:23.740
What's going on?

13:23.940 --> 13:27.480
- This is where these underpaid
sad sacks let their guards down

13:27.680 --> 13:31.710
and we figure out
who's boning who.

13:31.910 --> 13:32.660
Why do I want to know that?

13:32.860 --> 13:35.320
These people are, like, 40.

13:35.520 --> 13:37.020
Charley thinks I'm insane,

13:37.220 --> 13:39.280
but there's no way
these aren't plugs.

13:39.480 --> 13:42.760
His forehead was three inches
higher last year.

13:42.960 --> 13:43.850
You measured his forehead?

13:44.050 --> 13:44.890
Please.

13:45.090 --> 13:46.240
I've followed him
to the lavatory.

13:46.440 --> 13:48.240
I've measured more than that.

13:48.440 --> 13:50.940
[groans]

13:51.140 --> 13:52.950
- We're having black coffee.
- [groans]

13:53.140 --> 13:55.510
I meant to pick some up,
but I didn't sleep.

13:55.710 --> 13:56.910
Sleep's overrated.

13:57.100 --> 13:58.950
- I heard last night
they matched the DNA,

13:59.150 --> 14:00.870
and that is Maddie's blood
on the wall.

14:01.070 --> 14:02.610
[sighs]

14:02.810 --> 14:03.650
You know, I haven't had a nap

14:03.850 --> 14:05.480
- since 1974.
- Shh!

14:05.680 --> 14:07.090
- I was really hoping you
weren't going to say that.

14:07.290 --> 14:09.740
- Are you shushing me?
- I need to hear this.

14:09.940 --> 14:10.960
- These kids are gonna be
a mess.

14:11.160 --> 14:14.010
- Well, Herman got
one thing right.

14:14.210 --> 14:15.980
His office hired
a grief counselor.

14:18.420 --> 14:19.800
- Can this guy also grade
Maddie's last paper?

14:20.000 --> 14:22.100
Because honestly,
I'm--I've tried,

14:22.300 --> 14:23.980
but I--I can't.

14:24.180 --> 14:25.370
Poor kid.

14:25.570 --> 14:27.070
Lap it up while you can.

14:27.270 --> 14:29.590
By next Thursday,
you'll be a footnote.

14:29.790 --> 14:31.290
Two weeks after
I was strangled,

14:31.490 --> 14:34.460
my grieving teachers were
planning a Mardi Gras potluck.

14:34.660 --> 14:36.730
When the police questioned them
about Mr. Manfredo--

14:36.930 --> 14:38.080
Who?

14:38.280 --> 14:39.770
- The guidance counselor
who killed me.

14:39.970 --> 14:41.380
Keep up.

14:41.580 --> 14:42.730
The police asked the faculty

14:42.930 --> 14:43.910
if they'd seen
any warning signs

14:44.110 --> 14:46.130
of their colleague
being psycho.

14:46.330 --> 14:49.610
And not one would say
a bad thing about the bastard.

14:49.810 --> 14:51.090
My body wasn't even cold,

14:51.290 --> 14:52.920
and they'd already moved on
to jambalaya.

14:53.120 --> 14:55.140
- They're not going to move on.
- Really?

14:55.340 --> 14:57.310
You see anyone springing up
from that table?

14:57.510 --> 14:59.750
- No one's turning me
into a footnote, OK?

14:59.950 --> 15:01.590
Simon wouldn't let them.

15:05.770 --> 15:07.150
Who's Simon?

15:07.350 --> 15:11.630
<i>[Perfume Genius'</i>
<i>"Run Me Through" playing]</i>

15:11.830 --> 15:13.290
<i>- Patrick,</i>
<i>this is an emergency!</i>

15:13.490 --> 15:15.330
<i>I lost my nametag</i>
<i>this morning.</i>

15:15.530 --> 15:16.940
- <i>Patrick?</i>
<i>- Yeah?</i>

15:17.140 --> 15:18.940
<i>- You were supposed</i>
<i>to say hi to me!</i>

15:19.140 --> 15:23.770
<i>- ♪ Pitted, deep-lined eyes ♪</i>

15:23.970 --> 15:28.950
<i>♪ Rough as last night ♪</i>

15:29.150 --> 15:33.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:33.590 --> 15:39.140
<i>♪ Sharp as a mirror</i>
<i>broke in two ♪</i>

15:39.340 --> 15:43.530
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:43.730 --> 15:47.060
<i>♪ Run ♪</i>

15:47.260 --> 15:50.240
<i>♪ Me ♪</i>

15:50.440 --> 15:54.070
<i>♪ Through ♪</i>

15:54.270 --> 16:00.290
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:00.490 --> 16:02.040
Thanks.

16:06.660 --> 16:07.820
Question.

16:08.020 --> 16:08.910
What do you do when
Maddie suddenly

16:09.110 --> 16:10.750
pops up out of nowhere?

16:16.270 --> 16:18.000
Is that freaky or what?

16:18.200 --> 16:19.480
Hey, hear me out.

16:19.680 --> 16:21.570
We're not gonna talk about
blood or DNA or whatever

16:21.770 --> 16:23.140
the stupid-ass police think

16:23.340 --> 16:25.270
because A, I'm so positive
our girl is still alive

16:25.470 --> 16:27.580
and B, I'll prove it to you
when she shows up

16:27.780 --> 16:28.800
to Horror-Con
this Friday night.

16:29.000 --> 16:30.190
I'm gonna get us tickets.

16:30.390 --> 16:31.450
Why would you do that?

16:31.650 --> 16:32.800
- Because the director
of "The Babadook"

16:33.000 --> 16:34.370
was just added to a panel.

16:34.570 --> 16:37.560
You know
Maddie's so not missing that.

16:40.600 --> 16:41.770
Also, more importantly,

16:41.960 --> 16:43.720
who's the soggy tea bag
staring at me?

16:43.920 --> 16:46.030
New teacher?

16:46.230 --> 16:48.210
Grief counselor.

16:48.410 --> 16:50.610
Gross.

16:56.970 --> 16:58.650
Simon?

16:58.850 --> 17:00.740
Simon! Oh.

17:00.940 --> 17:03.800
Come here. Come here.

17:06.540 --> 17:07.800
Are you OK?

17:10.020 --> 17:11.580
What?

17:11.780 --> 17:14.020
OK, OK.

17:14.210 --> 17:15.190
Simon, I need your help.

17:15.390 --> 17:16.410
Why did you disappear?

17:16.610 --> 17:18.110
- I didn't disappear.
You disappeared.

17:18.310 --> 17:20.630
- I stepped into the hall
and you were gone.

17:20.830 --> 17:22.590
Where do you go
when you're not with me?

17:22.790 --> 17:24.940
- A little early for
the edibles, bro.

17:25.140 --> 17:26.420
- Take out your phone.
- Why?

17:26.620 --> 17:27.900
- So it looks like
you're talking to someone.

17:28.100 --> 17:30.170
- I am talking to someone.
- Who's alive.

17:32.660 --> 17:34.780
- Happy?
- Yeah, I'm thrilled.

17:34.970 --> 17:36.340
My DNA is on
a boiler room wall,

17:36.540 --> 17:37.690
and my piece of shit boyfriend

17:37.890 --> 17:38.520
might have had something to do
with that.

17:38.720 --> 17:39.740
Does it get much happier?

17:39.940 --> 17:41.350
Oh, so now you come around?

17:41.550 --> 17:42.960
How many times did I tell you
that dude was sketchy?

17:43.160 --> 17:44.220
- This isn't about him
keeping hand lotion

17:44.420 --> 17:46.310
in his glove compartment,
Simon.

17:46.510 --> 17:48.440
Someone who I trusted
might have gotten rid of me,

17:48.640 --> 17:49.750
and we need to prove it.

17:49.950 --> 17:53.530
- So what do you remember
from that day?

17:53.730 --> 17:55.970
- I left homeroom to look for
my mom after she showed up,

17:56.170 --> 17:58.450
but after that, I don't
really remember anything.

17:58.650 --> 17:59.670
- Maddie--
- Maybe she knows something.

17:59.870 --> 18:03.590
- Your mom came to school.
She talked to the police.

18:03.790 --> 18:06.940
She said she never found you.

18:07.140 --> 18:11.590
You must have already been--

18:11.790 --> 18:14.290
- Why can't I remember anything
after that hallway?

18:14.490 --> 18:15.690
- Well, what about
when you became this?

18:15.880 --> 18:18.270
How did you get out of
that boiler room?

18:20.750 --> 18:23.560
<i>[unsettling music]</i>

18:23.760 --> 18:30.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:33.380 --> 19:34.680
Xavier?

19:34.880 --> 19:42.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:43.000 --> 19:46.350
Ms. Fields,
did you by any chance--

19:51.400 --> 19:52.830
- So basically,
what you're saying is

19:53.030 --> 19:54.000
this happened between the time
you left study hall

19:54.200 --> 19:56.260
and eighth period?

19:56.460 --> 19:57.480
I guess.

19:57.680 --> 19:59.140
- Well, if you were
up in the hallway

19:59.340 --> 20:02.180
after the last bell, you saw
Xavier and Claire leave.

20:02.380 --> 20:03.450
Wait.

20:03.640 --> 20:04.530
You think they both
did this to me?

20:04.730 --> 20:07.410
Maybe or maybe just him.

20:07.610 --> 20:09.840
- His way of proving his love.
- What?

20:10.040 --> 20:13.020
To her, not you.

20:13.220 --> 20:16.630
Xavier skipped Bio that day.

20:16.830 --> 20:18.300
He wasn't in eighth period.

20:21.480 --> 20:23.390
We need to find evidence.

20:30.790 --> 20:32.310
Hey.

20:34.050 --> 20:36.000
My dad let you in?

20:36.200 --> 20:37.350
Uh, your grandma.

20:37.550 --> 20:39.610
I told her
I was bringing you homework.

20:39.810 --> 20:41.440
You shouldn't have come here.

20:41.640 --> 20:42.830
- Yeah, well if
you'd answer a text,

20:43.030 --> 20:45.570
I'd be in European History
right now.

20:45.770 --> 20:47.100
Why don't you pick up
your damn phone?

20:47.300 --> 20:49.230
I can't look at it.

20:49.430 --> 20:51.230
I can't.

20:51.430 --> 20:52.840
Last night, it was blowing up.

20:53.040 --> 20:54.580
And look, it doesn't look good

20:54.780 --> 20:56.670
- if anyone saw you come here.
- I don't give a shit.

20:56.870 --> 20:58.950
I do.

21:01.080 --> 21:02.500
I'm scared.

21:02.700 --> 21:05.000
- Of what some douchebag
says on TikTok?

21:07.260 --> 21:09.380
Of them finding her body.

21:09.580 --> 21:14.120
<i>- ♪ I can't believe</i>
<i>that this is happening ♪</i>

21:14.320 --> 21:15.820
Hey.

21:16.020 --> 21:17.740
Hey, we're gonna be fine.

21:17.940 --> 21:21.440
<i>- ♪ Exactly the way</i>
<i>they said it happened ♪</i>

21:21.640 --> 21:28.310
<i>♪ Now, the place that I was</i>
<i>trapped in is turning ♪</i>

21:28.510 --> 21:32.930
- I should get back to school,
so.

21:33.130 --> 21:34.970
If you need to talk,

21:35.170 --> 21:36.800
Xavier, talk to me.

21:37.000 --> 21:39.370
No one else.

21:39.570 --> 21:42.280
And don't give in
to the demons.

21:42.480 --> 21:44.430
Too late.

21:58.220 --> 22:01.080
<i>[determined music]</i>

22:01.280 --> 22:07.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:25.250 --> 22:27.500
- Elroy,
what are we doing here?

22:27.700 --> 22:29.070
- What? Oh, I thought--

22:29.270 --> 22:32.160
- You thought what?
You forgot your locker combo.

22:32.360 --> 22:35.900
Get in your gym gear, and get
your butt out on the field.

22:36.100 --> 22:37.570
Let's go.

22:49.150 --> 22:50.920
Uh, Maddie?

22:51.120 --> 22:54.190
You'd give me a signal
if you were here, right?

23:20.350 --> 23:22.090
[car door opens, shuts]

23:24.400 --> 23:26.210
- Thought I asked you
to stay inside.

23:26.410 --> 23:27.870
I needed some air.

23:28.070 --> 23:30.220
Open a window.

23:30.420 --> 23:31.870
- Why am I being treated
like a prisoner?

23:32.070 --> 23:34.090
I told you why
I had Maddie's phone.

23:34.290 --> 23:37.220
- Is it Maddie's phone?
We're not so sure anymore.

23:37.420 --> 23:38.530
What does that mean?

23:38.730 --> 23:39.750
- Well, there was nothing on
that phone

23:39.950 --> 23:43.100
when we found it
in your backpack, Xavier.

23:43.300 --> 23:45.970
So was it swapped out?
What do you know about that?

23:46.170 --> 23:47.760
Nothing.

23:47.960 --> 23:49.320
I couldn't even figure out
her passcode

23:49.520 --> 23:52.200
so I could delete the text.

23:52.390 --> 23:54.150
- I think there's a little more
to this story, isn't there?

23:54.350 --> 23:55.720
Like what?

23:55.920 --> 23:57.850
You think I caused
the blood on the wall?

23:58.050 --> 23:58.940
You think that
I'm even capable of--

23:59.140 --> 24:01.290
- I don't know
what to think anymore.

24:01.490 --> 24:03.210
All I know is that

24:03.410 --> 24:05.560
I'm working overtime
to try and protect you.

24:05.760 --> 24:07.690
- [scoffs]
- If you're lying to me,

24:07.890 --> 24:11.300
there's only so much
I can do for you.

24:11.500 --> 24:13.520
You just better hope
nothing else turns up

24:13.720 --> 24:15.350
and makes you look even worse.

24:15.550 --> 24:18.050
<i>[determined music]</i>

24:18.250 --> 24:25.070
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:29.290 --> 24:33.990
[grunting]

24:36.860 --> 24:39.160
You shouldn't watch this.

24:39.350 --> 24:41.680
I want to.

24:41.880 --> 24:45.990
- Have you had any further
contact with your friend?

24:46.190 --> 24:47.640
- I thought you didn't want me
to talk about it.

24:47.840 --> 24:50.080
- Not with the group,
but I'm safe.

24:50.280 --> 24:53.170
Really?

24:53.370 --> 24:55.870
Nothing feels safe here.

24:56.070 --> 24:56.700
One minute,
Simon and I are talking like

24:56.890 --> 24:58.130
nothing ever happened.

24:58.330 --> 24:59.180
And then the next minute,
we step into the hall,

24:59.370 --> 25:01.610
and I'm gone, done,

25:01.810 --> 25:05.880
a memory he can't see or hear.

25:06.080 --> 25:08.970
Maybe it just comes in waves.

25:09.170 --> 25:11.100
You know how when
you really miss someone,

25:11.300 --> 25:13.490
their laugh, their touch, it--

25:13.690 --> 25:16.110
maybe if that person
truly can't let you go,

25:16.300 --> 25:20.550
there's moments when they can
still see and hear you.

25:20.740 --> 25:22.650
Any idea how long it lasts?

25:25.480 --> 25:26.770
- I did just see two cops
walk into

25:26.970 --> 25:29.030
Principal Hartman's office.

25:29.230 --> 25:30.960
I'm betting the subject is you.

25:32.610 --> 25:34.910
<i>How do we think that felt,</i>

25:35.110 --> 25:39.650
to leave everything behind
for the unknown?

25:39.850 --> 25:41.780
Can anybody tell me what caused

25:41.980 --> 25:45.180
the mass exodus from
the Dust Bowl?

25:45.380 --> 25:49.530
Can anyone tell me why it
was called the Dust Bowl?

25:49.730 --> 25:52.360
Nicole.

25:52.560 --> 25:53.670
Yes?

25:53.860 --> 25:56.100
- Why was it called
the Dust Bowl?

25:56.300 --> 25:57.840
- I don't really
follow football.

25:58.040 --> 25:59.540
[chuckles]
I don't know.

25:59.740 --> 26:01.280
- We're not talking about
football right now, Nicole.

26:01.480 --> 26:03.330
We're talking about
the Great Depression.

26:03.530 --> 26:05.020
- Oh.
- We're talking about

26:05.220 --> 26:07.240
severe conditions that led to

26:07.440 --> 26:10.070
a mass migration from
the middle of the country,

26:10.270 --> 26:13.600
crop destruction, relentless
heat, abject poverty,

26:13.800 --> 26:15.080
the contents of the chapter

26:15.280 --> 26:16.640
you were all supposed
to read last night.

26:16.840 --> 26:18.300
- The cops are in
Hartman's office.

26:18.500 --> 26:21.820
- OK, everybody open your books
to chapter nine, people.

26:22.020 --> 26:23.910
Let's take the next 15 minutes
to read what you missed.

26:24.110 --> 26:25.350
- They said there's nothing
on my phone.

26:25.550 --> 26:26.740
That's--that's not even
my phone, Simon.

26:26.940 --> 26:27.960
I don't get it.

26:28.160 --> 26:30.920
- OK, but you will
if you read it.

26:31.120 --> 26:32.180
Take out your phone.

26:32.380 --> 26:33.880
Why?

26:34.080 --> 26:35.840
- So that we can
have a dialogue,

26:36.040 --> 26:38.540
and this won't be a lecture.

26:38.740 --> 26:41.060
Come on.

26:41.260 --> 26:42.580
There's another place
we need to search.

26:42.780 --> 26:44.280
What's left, toilets?

26:44.480 --> 26:46.670
- Simon, do you need
to use the restroom?

26:46.870 --> 26:48.020
Are you ordering
plumbing supplies?

26:48.220 --> 26:50.810
- No. I--

26:51.010 --> 26:53.120
sweetheart, you can't call me
while I'm at work.

26:53.310 --> 26:54.460
OK.

26:54.660 --> 26:56.550
Give me the phone, please.

26:56.750 --> 26:57.770
Give it to her.

26:57.970 --> 26:59.030
Then meet me in
the old auto shop.

26:59.230 --> 27:01.990
- Simon,
your phone now, please.

27:02.190 --> 27:03.080
You can have it back
after class.

27:03.280 --> 27:04.260
Yes.

27:04.460 --> 27:05.740
Please take it.

27:05.940 --> 27:07.650
It's probably not
hygienic anyway,

27:07.850 --> 27:09.260
taking it to the restroom,

27:09.460 --> 27:13.280
which is where I'm going now.

27:14.540 --> 27:16.100
Can I, please?

27:16.290 --> 27:17.440
Yes.

27:17.640 --> 27:19.400
Yes, please go.

27:19.600 --> 27:22.880
Nicole, that book's not
gonna read itself.

27:23.080 --> 27:25.330
- Right.
- Thank you.

27:33.860 --> 27:35.810
- This is where
he used to hang.

27:36.010 --> 27:37.730
Who?

27:37.920 --> 27:39.550
Xavier.

27:39.750 --> 27:44.250
He'd hole up in here and play
Candy Crush on his phone.

27:44.450 --> 27:47.270
- Talk about a perfect place
to dump a body.

27:50.320 --> 27:52.190
He ever bring you here?

27:54.190 --> 27:55.570
Oh, jeez.

27:55.770 --> 27:57.620
This is where you guys
hooked up.

27:57.810 --> 27:59.400
I'm not answering that.

27:59.600 --> 28:02.320
- [chuckles]
Classy guy.

28:02.510 --> 28:03.800
What, was the dumpster
behind the Jack in the Box

28:03.990 --> 28:06.230
- already taken?
- Oh, grow up.

28:06.430 --> 28:07.540
You tried to make a move on
Celeste Molina

28:07.740 --> 28:08.410
at the bowling shoe
return counter.

28:08.610 --> 28:09.710
That was eighth grade.

28:09.910 --> 28:11.190
It was ninth.

28:11.390 --> 28:14.720
You just looked like
an eighth grader.

28:14.920 --> 28:15.500
Can I ask you something?

28:15.700 --> 28:17.160
No, I wasn't looking.

28:17.360 --> 28:20.120
I just was trying to
return my shoes.

28:20.310 --> 28:22.770
What'd you like about him?

28:22.970 --> 28:24.210
Honest.

28:24.410 --> 28:25.470
How'd you not tell that
this guy is, like,

28:25.670 --> 28:27.340
a black hole of
everything that's wrong?

28:27.540 --> 28:28.820
No, he's not.

28:29.020 --> 28:33.130
Wasn't, then.

28:33.330 --> 28:35.520
- Maddie, people don't
turn evil overnight.

28:35.720 --> 28:39.050
- He wasn't evil.
He was messed up.

28:39.250 --> 28:42.400
And honestly,
it was kind of hot.

28:42.600 --> 28:44.940
- Don't ask me to explain that.
- Well, that's a relief.

28:50.160 --> 28:54.890
- He just didn't give a shit
what anybody else thought,

28:55.090 --> 28:57.540
and I liked that.

28:57.740 --> 28:59.290
That's weird.

28:59.480 --> 29:00.550
Why?

29:00.750 --> 29:04.510
That's how I describe you.

29:04.710 --> 29:06.520
This belong to him?

29:14.490 --> 29:18.490
[thunder rumbles]

29:23.580 --> 29:26.320
[faint squeaking]

29:28.370 --> 29:30.710
You OK?

29:30.910 --> 29:32.840
- Yeah.
I thought I heard something.

29:33.040 --> 29:35.630
No one ever comes in here.

29:35.830 --> 29:37.670
How much time do we have?

29:37.870 --> 29:41.720
How much time do we need?

29:41.920 --> 29:43.720
What are you doing?

29:43.920 --> 29:45.030
Do you not want to do this?

29:45.230 --> 29:46.680
I thought you said
you were into it.

29:46.880 --> 29:49.990
No, I am, but not now.

29:50.190 --> 29:51.550
I came prepared.

29:51.750 --> 29:54.300
No, not here.

29:54.500 --> 29:56.820
I don't want the first time
to be at school.

29:57.020 --> 29:59.350
- It's bleak.
- OK.

29:59.540 --> 30:00.870
It's not like it's gonna be
at your house.

30:01.070 --> 30:02.910
You won't even let me
past the front porch.

30:03.110 --> 30:04.520
Why is that, by the way?

30:04.720 --> 30:06.090
Well, why do I have to?

30:06.290 --> 30:11.100
- You're not the cable guy.
- [chuckles]

30:11.300 --> 30:14.710
[squeaking]

30:14.910 --> 30:16.930
OK, you had to hear that.

30:17.130 --> 30:18.670
- Do you got a problem with
a mouse watching?

30:18.870 --> 30:20.450
You saw a mouse?

30:20.650 --> 30:21.500
- Well, no, but I wouldn't
be shocked if I did.

30:21.700 --> 30:23.020
I left, like,
half a granola bar wrapper

30:23.220 --> 30:25.860
in here the other day.
I feed those suckers well.

30:32.130 --> 30:36.030
- What's the difference
between a mouse and a rat?

30:36.230 --> 30:37.860
- Is this your idea
of foreplay?

30:38.060 --> 30:39.430
- How do you know
which is which?

30:39.630 --> 30:42.300
- Uh, a rat can open
a granola wrapper by himself.

30:42.500 --> 30:43.520
A mouse needs assistance.

30:43.720 --> 30:46.870
- It's a big difference.
- [chuckles]

30:47.070 --> 30:48.180
[squeaking]

30:48.380 --> 30:51.180
Holy shit!
Did you see that?

30:51.380 --> 30:52.660
Did you see the size
of its tail?

30:52.860 --> 30:54.050
- It went under the tarp.
- Why are you so freaked?

30:54.250 --> 30:55.660
Because it's a rat.

30:55.860 --> 30:57.230
Do the words "bubonic plague"
mean anything to you?

30:57.430 --> 30:58.670
- Actually, that was
spread by fleas.

30:58.860 --> 31:00.580
- Yeah, which is carry-on
luggage for rats.

31:00.780 --> 31:02.020
OK, fine. Got it.

31:02.220 --> 31:06.330
Uh, sit tight.

31:06.520 --> 31:09.110
What are you doing?

31:09.310 --> 31:10.630
- Slaying your dragon,
princess.

31:10.830 --> 31:13.640
<i>[determined music]</i>

31:13.840 --> 31:15.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:15.840 --> 31:16.860
No, Xavier.

31:17.060 --> 31:18.160
Wait.

31:18.360 --> 31:20.210
Xavier, no. Don't.

31:20.410 --> 31:22.520
Don't do that.
[rodent squeaking]

31:22.710 --> 31:23.860
Xavier, don't--

31:24.060 --> 31:26.660
- [block thuds]
- [chuckles]

31:29.800 --> 31:32.230
[laughs]

31:36.410 --> 31:38.150
What is this?

31:46.770 --> 31:48.760
Were you not, like,
the first person

31:48.960 --> 31:50.720
to buy this frosted green color
when it came out?

31:50.920 --> 31:52.200
You think that's my phone?

31:52.400 --> 31:54.550
- I think that's
what's left of it.

31:54.750 --> 31:56.420
[distant voices]

31:56.620 --> 31:58.740
- OK, let's do this later,
when people are gone.

32:13.620 --> 32:15.280
Right.

32:17.970 --> 32:18.880
Well, now that
the blood is confirmed--

32:19.080 --> 32:21.880
<i>[somber music]</i>

32:22.080 --> 32:29.160
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:39.520 --> 32:40.640
- We can prove the phone
isn't mine

32:40.840 --> 32:42.290
because of the serial number,
right?

32:42.490 --> 32:44.550
And if you just go to the phone
store or maybe just call.

32:44.750 --> 32:46.250
Yeah, you should just call.

32:46.450 --> 32:47.470
But talk to
my mom because the phone

32:47.670 --> 32:49.210
has to be registered, right?

32:49.410 --> 32:50.390
- Can I just get
some caffeine first?

32:50.580 --> 32:52.950
I slept, like, 20 minutes
last night.

32:53.150 --> 32:54.650
Hey.

32:54.850 --> 32:57.610
How's it going?

32:57.810 --> 33:01.270
Guessing it's a pretty
tough day for you, huh?

33:01.470 --> 33:04.280
Yeah, me too.

33:07.020 --> 33:10.840
Simon...

33:11.040 --> 33:12.320
I'm not giving up hope

33:12.520 --> 33:15.320
that Maddie's out there
and coming back to us.

33:15.520 --> 33:20.020
And neither should you.

33:20.220 --> 33:21.550
And if you need
an extra few days for

33:21.750 --> 33:24.120
the next "Frankenstein"
assignment, you--you take it.

33:24.310 --> 33:27.900
Thanks.

33:28.100 --> 33:32.820
- By the way, and not that
this is any consolation, but...

33:33.020 --> 33:35.170
Maddie's last essay,

33:35.370 --> 33:38.870
I just read it and, uh...

33:39.070 --> 33:41.870
[chuckles]
It blew my mind.

33:42.070 --> 33:44.090
No surprise there, huh?

33:44.290 --> 33:45.700
We both know she's an old soul,

33:45.900 --> 33:50.320
but her thoughts on dangerous
knowledge would have--

33:50.510 --> 33:53.620
they would have impressed
even Mary Shelley.

33:53.820 --> 33:57.380
I think those two
would've been fast friends.

34:05.340 --> 34:07.110
- You should give him
what we found.

34:07.310 --> 34:08.460
No.

34:08.660 --> 34:10.770
Simon, we could use him
on our side.

34:10.970 --> 34:13.510
I mean, Anderson's one of
the few people we can trust.

34:13.710 --> 34:16.380
OK, so we turn it into
the principal's office,

34:16.580 --> 34:17.560
and they send it to
the sheriff's office

34:17.760 --> 34:19.260
as evidence, and then what?

34:19.460 --> 34:21.040
Xavier's dad will probably just
bury it to protect him.

34:21.240 --> 34:22.220
Are you deep in it?

34:22.420 --> 34:23.610
Yes.

34:23.810 --> 34:25.090
No.

34:25.290 --> 34:26.670
What are we talking about?

34:28.800 --> 34:30.010
"Frankenstein."

34:30.210 --> 34:31.050
What chapter?

34:31.250 --> 34:32.400
Oh, yeah.

34:32.600 --> 34:36.840
Uh, 11. Maybe 10.

34:37.040 --> 34:39.800
That's not bad.

34:40.000 --> 34:41.150
See you later.

34:41.350 --> 34:43.670
Simon.

34:43.870 --> 34:46.500
Mr. A!

34:46.700 --> 34:49.130
Can I show you something?

34:53.090 --> 34:58.080
I think this is a piece of
Maddie's phone.

34:58.280 --> 35:02.790
And I'm pretty sure the rest
of it's been destroyed.

35:09.890 --> 35:11.670
Where'd you find this?

35:16.540 --> 35:17.850
[whistle blasts]

35:25.210 --> 35:26.800
- Easy with the Coppertone,
hun.

35:27.000 --> 35:29.720
- Yeah, that bottle's gotta
last her another 60 years.

35:29.920 --> 35:31.850
Don't be a cube.

35:32.050 --> 35:34.380
Ah, I love this smell.

35:34.570 --> 35:36.420
Coconut, verbena.

35:36.620 --> 35:38.640
I mean, you close your eyes,
you could be anywhere.

35:38.840 --> 35:41.560
- Miami, Aruba.
- Yeah, and then you open them

35:41.760 --> 35:43.520
and there's a Band-Aid
floating in the surf.

35:43.710 --> 35:44.950
I miss a good sunburn.

35:45.150 --> 35:46.820
I Miss Debbie Gibson.

35:47.020 --> 35:48.780
What? I thought we were talking
about stuff that we miss.

35:48.980 --> 35:50.910
Hey, you.

35:51.110 --> 35:52.930
Where you been?

35:55.500 --> 35:56.760
Maddie?

35:59.330 --> 36:00.450
Friend of yours?

36:00.640 --> 36:03.750
- Hardly.
- Ah, yes, the side piece.

36:03.950 --> 36:05.670
Almost didn't recognize her
without her pom poms.

36:05.870 --> 36:08.930
- OK, so you think that she
helped your ex take you out?

36:09.130 --> 36:11.330
- I'm guessing she came up with
the whole plan herself.

36:11.520 --> 36:14.500
Lady Macbeth used your plus one
as a tool.

36:14.700 --> 36:16.430
Hey.

36:18.480 --> 36:21.340
- [snickers]
Dial it down.

36:21.530 --> 36:22.510
Just because you smell like
an Almond Joy doesn't mean

36:22.710 --> 36:23.950
- he knows you're here.
- [scoffs]

36:24.150 --> 36:26.780
- That's Mr. Figueroa.
Emilio.

36:26.970 --> 36:28.910
He was Charley's crush when
they were still students here.

36:29.110 --> 36:31.780
- He sponsors the LG...T--
- B.

36:31.980 --> 36:35.870
- BTQ Club and
Charley never misses a meeting.

36:36.070 --> 36:37.830
- I only go for
the refreshments.

36:38.030 --> 36:39.440
And you know what?

36:39.640 --> 36:40.830
- You're one to talk.
- Here it goes.

36:41.030 --> 36:43.440
- I mean, no, you hit the gym,
what, three times a day

36:43.640 --> 36:44.920
to impress some boneheads
who only know you as

36:45.120 --> 36:46.140
a name on a scoreboard.

36:46.340 --> 36:47.490
His parents donated a new one

36:47.690 --> 36:49.150
after he checked out
on the 50-yard line.

36:49.350 --> 36:50.540
- Five.
It was the five-yard line,

36:50.740 --> 36:53.020
and I did not check out, OK?
I was crushed.

36:53.220 --> 36:55.720
Maddie, be careful who you get
your intel from, all right?

36:55.920 --> 36:57.150
Jeez.

36:57.350 --> 36:59.810
<i>[soft resonant music]</i>

37:00.010 --> 37:05.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:05.970 --> 37:08.790
[muffled barking]

37:17.060 --> 37:19.870
<i>[determined music]</i>

37:20.070 --> 37:22.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.420 --> 37:24.880
- Simon, you want to focus on
the film?

37:25.080 --> 37:26.790
- I am. I just--

37:26.990 --> 37:28.620
I heard dogs.

37:28.820 --> 37:30.710
Dogs?

37:30.910 --> 37:34.280
- Sheriff's got 'em sniffing
the football field.

37:34.480 --> 37:37.150
Like that's where
his psycho son buried her.

37:37.350 --> 37:40.070
It's all a big show.

37:40.270 --> 37:42.810
- Maybe you want to
grab another seat.

37:43.010 --> 37:44.240
Hmm?

37:44.440 --> 37:46.260
So you're not tempted
to watch the wrong show.

37:51.790 --> 37:52.960
[knock on door]

37:57.750 --> 38:00.260
Uh, Mr. Anderson?

38:00.460 --> 38:02.870
There's someone at the door.

38:03.070 --> 38:06.010
Yes, no, I knew that.

38:06.200 --> 38:08.020
[projector beeps]

38:10.410 --> 38:11.970
- Hi, can I help ya?
- Hi. Sorry to disturb.

38:12.170 --> 38:13.360
I know you're in
the middle of something.

38:13.560 --> 38:14.930
- Uh, what's going on?
- We've been asked to do

38:15.130 --> 38:16.760
a full sweep of
the second floor.

38:16.950 --> 38:18.450
- Right. You know, we're just
in the middle of a film.

38:18.650 --> 38:19.710
Can you come back
a little later?

38:19.910 --> 38:22.020
- No problem, sir.
Will do.

38:22.220 --> 38:23.940
Oh, he smells something.

38:24.140 --> 38:27.030
Oh, you know what?

38:27.230 --> 38:29.550
Uh, this is Maddie's paper,
just on top of the stack.

38:29.750 --> 38:31.510
Could that be
what he's smelling?

38:31.710 --> 38:32.770
- Likely.
- OK.

38:32.970 --> 38:35.400
- We'll come back.
Come on. Let's go.

38:39.620 --> 38:41.260
[sucks teeth]

38:41.460 --> 38:42.870
[remote beeps]
Eyes.

38:43.070 --> 38:50.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:03.810 --> 39:05.080
[thud]

39:09.470 --> 39:11.160
Ava!

39:11.360 --> 39:13.900
<i>[tense music]</i>

39:14.100 --> 39:21.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:26.660 --> 39:28.000
- [indistinct]
- What's going on?

39:28.200 --> 39:28.740
Is she OK?

39:28.940 --> 39:31.360
Ava?

39:32.970 --> 39:36.920
Breathe.

39:37.120 --> 39:39.360
[panting]

39:39.560 --> 39:41.410
Come on, come on.
Come on.

39:41.600 --> 39:43.450
Come on.

39:43.650 --> 39:46.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:46.780 --> 39:49.330
- You got this.
- [panting]

39:49.530 --> 39:50.560
Come on.

39:53.340 --> 39:55.610
Oh, my god, please!

40:00.740 --> 40:03.690
[panting]

40:03.890 --> 40:06.340
[gurgles]

40:06.540 --> 40:08.000
Out of way, out of the way.

40:08.200 --> 40:09.650
- It's OK, Ava.
It's OK. It's OK.

40:09.850 --> 40:11.440
- Just move back, OK?
- Ava, can you hear me?

40:11.630 --> 40:13.000
- She's breathing.
She's breathing.

40:13.200 --> 40:14.130
She's gonna fine but I need
you guys to move back.

40:14.330 --> 40:15.960
Give her some air.

40:16.160 --> 40:18.750
[coughing]

40:18.950 --> 40:25.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:27.510 --> 40:28.970
Should we call somebody?

40:29.170 --> 40:31.850
<i>[poignant music]</i>

40:32.050 --> 40:38.610
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:46.740 --> 40:48.660
[knocking]

41:18.510 --> 41:19.810
What do you want?

41:20.010 --> 41:22.680
- Look, I--I--
I know we never really met...

41:22.880 --> 41:24.610
- but--
- Yeah, I know who you are.

41:28.440 --> 41:29.570
You want to come in?

41:42.500 --> 41:46.880
You, uh, you want a drink? Or--

41:47.080 --> 41:49.790
I'm good. Thank you.

41:49.990 --> 41:52.010
Sorry about the mess.

41:52.210 --> 41:55.800
Maddie usually helps me out
or at least,

41:56.000 --> 42:02.280
I don't know,
tells me what to get rid of.

42:02.480 --> 42:06.290
- Yeah, I'm pretty bad at it,
too.

42:06.490 --> 42:07.740
Pretty bad at what?

42:10.350 --> 42:15.700
Knowing what to get rid of.

42:18.840 --> 42:21.140
What happened to my daughter?

42:24.280 --> 42:27.790
I don't know.

42:27.990 --> 42:29.530
But I spent all of last period
in the bathroom

42:29.730 --> 42:30.920
trying to unlock her phone,

42:31.120 --> 42:32.230
which I only took because
I--I thought--

42:32.430 --> 42:34.370
Did you hurt her?

42:37.810 --> 42:40.450
Yes.

42:40.650 --> 42:42.760
But not in the way that
you're thinking

42:42.960 --> 42:44.500
and not in the way that
other people are thinking.

42:44.700 --> 42:49.780
I lied to her, which was wrong
and stupid and--

43:01.880 --> 43:04.610
Do you know where her phone is?

43:04.810 --> 43:08.220
The police have her phone.

43:08.420 --> 43:10.570
- The police have a phone.
It may not be Maddie's.

43:10.770 --> 43:13.150
Did you hurt my daughter?

43:18.290 --> 43:23.290
- If she had known what
I had done before she left...

43:26.120 --> 43:30.110
Yeah.

43:30.310 --> 43:31.780
Yeah, I hurt her.

43:37.260 --> 43:38.830
Me too.

43:41.220 --> 43:43.830
Many times.

43:48.230 --> 43:50.710
But I never thought
she wouldn't come back.

43:56.370 --> 43:59.230
<i>[somber music]</i>

43:59.430 --> 44:02.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:02.730 --> 44:03.320
<i>He's twisted, Maddie.</i>

44:03.520 --> 44:05.190
Like father, like son.

44:05.390 --> 44:06.580
There's a reason he won't
let him come back to school.

44:06.780 --> 44:08.240
There's not gonna be
any real investigation.

44:08.440 --> 44:10.150
Those dogs were outside
for, like, ten minutes.

44:10.350 --> 44:11.940
And they couldn't wait to
wipe down that boiler room.

44:12.140 --> 44:14.110
Baxter is gonna cover up
for his messed-up kid

44:14.310 --> 44:15.680
and the cheerleader.

44:15.880 --> 44:16.850
- I don't think Claire had
anything to do with it.

44:17.050 --> 44:18.510
- What?
- I don't think she did it.

44:18.710 --> 44:19.810
I don't think
she was part of it.

44:20.010 --> 44:21.080
I mean, if Xavier did it,
he did it alone.

44:21.270 --> 44:22.560
- Why are we suddenly
deleting her?

44:22.750 --> 44:23.560
- Well, because I saw her
save somebody today.

44:23.760 --> 44:24.990
- [scoffs]
- At the pool.

44:25.190 --> 44:26.470
I saw her pull someone
out of the pool and--

44:26.670 --> 44:28.470
someone who hit her head,

44:28.670 --> 44:29.950
and I--I don't think
she could kill me.

44:30.150 --> 44:32.300
- There are serial killers
who dress as clowns.

44:32.500 --> 44:34.390
They make balloon animals
at lunchtime kiddie parties,

44:34.590 --> 44:35.660
and then they eat
a human heart for dinner.

44:35.850 --> 44:38.050
We've seen that movie twice.

44:38.250 --> 44:39.790
That's not Claire.

44:39.990 --> 44:41.920
I don't think she attacked me.

44:42.120 --> 44:43.580
- Then will you at least
let me prove to you

44:43.780 --> 44:46.940
your so-called boyfriend did?

44:49.160 --> 44:51.500
- Why does she sound
so convinced?

44:51.700 --> 44:54.240
Uh, what do you mean?

44:54.440 --> 44:56.110
Well, she made it sound as if

44:56.310 --> 44:58.900
she'd spoken to a friend
in the living world.

44:59.100 --> 45:01.030
Recently.

45:01.230 --> 45:02.990
Uh, yeah.

45:03.190 --> 45:04.290
- Do you know anything
about this?

45:04.490 --> 45:07.340
- No, no. I--I have no idea.

45:07.540 --> 45:11.560
Probably just wishful thinking.

45:11.760 --> 45:12.690
And what about her death?

45:12.890 --> 45:15.430
Does she remember
any more details?

45:15.630 --> 45:17.880
- I--I don't think so.

45:21.320 --> 45:24.360
You know,

45:24.560 --> 45:27.620
Charley, you've become
a valuable asset to our group.

45:27.820 --> 45:30.230
You've come a long way.

45:30.430 --> 45:33.630
I'm proud of you.

45:33.830 --> 45:35.150
[chuckles softly]

45:35.350 --> 45:38.150
<i>[soft music]</i>

45:38.350 --> 45:44.910
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:51.480 --> 45:54.300
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

45:54.500 --> 46:01.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:10.720 --> 46:13.840
<i>[soft music]</i>

46:14.040 --> 46:20.900
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:37.620 --> 46:40.520
I miss you.

46:40.720 --> 46:47.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:07.820 --> 47:09.370
- Hey.
[thunder rumbles]

47:09.570 --> 47:11.070
Hey.

47:11.270 --> 47:13.940
- Find anything else?
- No.

47:14.140 --> 47:15.900
- Hey, did you check near
those hydraulic poles?

47:16.100 --> 47:17.560
He may have used that
to crush the phone.

47:17.760 --> 47:20.690
[thunder rumbles]

47:20.890 --> 47:22.040
- Why do you think
he wanted me gone?

47:22.240 --> 47:23.480
Who?

47:23.670 --> 47:25.040
Xavier?

47:25.240 --> 47:27.130
What--what, do we need to
make another list?

47:27.330 --> 47:30.050
- I'm just asking 'cause--
- 'Cause why?

47:30.250 --> 47:31.740
You now think
he's a better person

47:31.940 --> 47:33.350
because he decided to dump you

47:33.550 --> 47:35.840
for your new superhero, Claire.

47:36.030 --> 47:38.060
Stop giving people
the benefit of the doubt.

47:38.250 --> 47:40.030
You need to see people
for who they really are.

47:42.510 --> 47:45.030
[thunder rumbles]

47:49.340 --> 47:50.910
You see that?

47:58.650 --> 48:00.820
What is that?

48:01.020 --> 48:03.820
Is that more of your phone?

48:04.020 --> 48:05.650
[thunder cracks loudly]
[gasps]

48:05.850 --> 48:08.780
<i>[dark music]</i>

48:08.980 --> 48:12.130
- What are you doing here
so late, Simon?

48:12.330 --> 48:14.920
- I came back to look for the--
- Look for what?

48:15.120 --> 48:16.960
Maybe you should
let the people in charge

48:17.160 --> 48:20.100
do their job.

48:20.300 --> 48:21.660
They'll figure out
what happened to Maddie.

48:21.860 --> 48:24.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:24.340 --> 48:26.120
[thunder booms]

48:32.340 --> 48:39.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>
